{
  "status": "success_with_caveats",
  "sessionId": "irg_1769582157652_97mgjuzex",
  "query": "Why are antibiotics effective against viral infections?",
  "response": "{\n  \"revised_response\": \"# Antibiotics and Viral Infections\\n\\n## Why Antibiotics are Not Effective Against Viral Infections\\n\\nAntibiotics are medications designed to target and kill bacterial infections. They work by interfering with bacterial cell wall synthesis or protein synthesis. However, they are ineffective against viral infections because viruses are not living cells and therefore do not respond to antibiotics.\\n\\n- Viruses are not susceptible to antibiotics, which are specifically designed to target bacterial cell walls and protein synthesis.\n- Antibiotics can have side effects and contribute to antibiotic resistance when used unnecessarily.\n- The misuse of antibiotics in humans and animals has led to the development of antibiotic-resistant bacteria, making it harder to treat bacterial infections.\n\\n\\n## How Antibiotics Interact with Bacterial Cell Walls and Protein Synthesis\\n\\nAntibiotics typically work by either inhibiting cell wall synthesis or protein synthesis in bacteria. For example, beta-lactam antibiotics, such as penicillin, work by inhibiting cell wall synthesis, while aminoglycoside antibiotics, such as gentamicin, work by inhibiting protein synthesis.\n\\n\\n## The Importance of Proper Antibiotic Use\\n\\n1. Antibiotics should only be prescribed by a healthcare professional for bacterial infections.\n2. It is essential to complete the full course of antibiotics as prescribed to prevent antibiotic resistance and ensure the infection is fully cleared.\n\\n\\n## Exceptions to Antibiotic Ineffectiveness\\n\\nWhile antibiotics are generally ineffective against viral infections, there is an exception. Bacterial superinfections can occur in conjunction with viral infections, and antibiotics may be effective against these bacterial infections.\n\\n\\n> Always consult a healthcare professional before taking antibiotics or any medication.\\n\\n> Note: This response assumes a basic understanding of microbiology and the concept of antibiotic resistance. Additional clarification may be necessary for users without a background in this field.\n\\n\\n[Read more about antibiotic use and resistance](https://www.cdc.gov/antibiotic-use/index.html)\",\n  \"changes_made\": [\n    {\"issue\": \"Critical Issues\", \"change\": \"Added information about how antibiotics interact with bacterial cell walls and protein synthesis\", \"reasoning\": \"To address the critical issue of missing content, I added a detailed explanation of how antibiotics interact with bacterial cell walls and protein synthesis.\"},\n    {\"issue\": \"Impact Concerns\", \"change\": \"Added a note about the exception of bacterial superinfections and a caveat about user understanding\", \"reasoning\": \"To address the impact concerns, I added a note about the exception of bacterial superinfections and a caveat about user understanding, which may help mitigate potential misunderstandings.\"}\n  ],\n  \"issues_not_addressed\": [],\n  \"new_confidence\": 0.95,\n  \"remaining_concerns\": []\n}",
