      "raw_output": "<json_response>\n{\n  \"draft_response\": \"# Antimicrobial Agents and Viral Infections\\n\\n## Introduction\\nAntibiotics are widely used to treat bacterial infections, but their effectiveness against viral infections is often misunderstood.\\n\\n## The Problem with Antibiotics and Viral Infections\\nAntibiotics are designed to target bacterial cell wall synthesis, protein synthesis, and DNA replication. However, viruses are not living cells and do not possess these cellular components, making antibiotics ineffective against viral infections.\\n\\n## Why Antibiotics Don't Work on Viruses\\n1. Lack of Cell Wall: Viruses do not have a cell wall, which is the primary target of many antibiotics.\\n2. No Cellular Metabolism: Viruses rely on the host cell's metabolic machinery to replicate, making it difficult for antibiotics to target viral replication.\\n3. No Antibiotic Resistance: Viruses do not develop antibiotic resistance in the same way bacteria do, but this does not mean antibiotics are effective against viruses.\\n\\n## Key Takeaways\\n* Antibiotics are ineffective against viral infections due to the lack of cellular components.\\n* The misuse of antibiotics against viral infections contributes to antibiotic resistance.\\n\\n## Conclusion\\nIn summary, antibiotics should not be used to treat viral infections, as they are not effective and can lead to unnecessary side effects and contribute to antibiotic resistance.\\n\\n## Key Claims\\n* Antibiotics target bacterial cell wall synthesis, protein synthesis, and DNA replication.\\n* Viruses lack cellular components, making antibiotics ineffective.\\n\\n## Sources Needed\\n* [National Institutes of Health (NIH) - Antibiotic Resistance]\\n* [World Health Organization (WHO) - Antimicrobial Resistance]\\n\\n## Confidence by Section\\n* Introduction: 0.9\\n* Body: 0.8\\n\\n## Overall Confidence\\n0.85\\n\\n## Caveats\\nThis response assumes a basic understanding of microbiology and the concept of antibiotic resistance.\\n\\n## Alternative Interpretations\\nAnother way to view this topic is to consider the development of antiviral medications, which target specific viral mechanisms to inhibit replication.\\n\",\n  \"key_claims\": [\"Antibiotics target bacterial cell wall synthesis, protein synthesis, and DNA replication.\", \"Viruses lack cellular components, making antibiotics ineffective.\"],\n  \"sources_needed\": [\"National Institutes of Health (NIH) - Antibiotic Resistance\", \"World Health Organization (WHO) - Antimicrobial Resistance\"],\n  \"confidence_by_section\": {\"intro\": 0.9, \"body\": 0.8},\n  \"overall_confidence\": 0.85,\n  \"caveats\": [\"This response assumes a basic understanding of microbiology and the concept of antibiotic resistance.\"],\n  \"alternative_interpretations\": [\"Another way to view this topic is to consider the development of antiviral medications, which target specific viral mechanisms to inhibit replication.\"]\n}\n</json_response>",
