      "content": {
        "draft_response": "# Why Antibiotics are Ineffective Against Viral Infections\n\n## Introduction\nAntibiotics are commonly used to treat bacterial infections, but they are ineffective against viral infections. This is because antibiotics target bacterial cells, not viral cells.\n\n## Background\nViral infections occur when a virus enters the body and starts to replicate. Viruses are made up of genetic material (either DNA or RNA) surrounded by a protein coat. In contrast, bacterial cells have a cell wall and a defined nucleus. Antibiotics work by interfering with bacterial cell wall synthesis or protein synthesis, which ultimately kills the bacterial cell.\n\n## Key Differences\n1. Cell structure: Bacterial cells have a cell wall and a defined nucleus, while viral cells do not.\n2. Replication mechanism: Viruses replicate by hijacking the host cell's machinery, whereas bacteria replicate by dividing and growing.\n3. Response to antibiotics: Bacteria respond to antibiotics by producing enzymes to inactivate them, while viruses do not.\n\n## Conclusion\nIn summary, antibiotics are ineffective against viral infections because they target bacterial cells, not viral cells. This highlights the importance of selecting the correct treatment for a given infection.\n\n## Sources Needed\n- [National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases](https://www.niaid.nih.gov/)\n- [Centers for Disease Control and Prevention](https://www.cdc.gov/)\n\n## Confidence by Section\n- Introduction: 0.9\n- Background: 0.8\n- Key Differences: 0.9\n- Conclusion: 0.9\n\n## Overall Confidence\n0.85\n\n## Caveats\nThis response assumes that the reader is familiar with the basic concepts of bacteria and viruses.\n\n## Alternative Interpretations\nAnother way to view this topic is to consider the concept of antiviral medications, which are designed to target viral infections directly.\n",
        "key_claims": [
          "Antibiotics target bacterial cells, not viral cells.",
          "Bacterial cells have a cell wall and a defined nucleus, while viral cells do not."
        ],
        "sources_needed": [
          "National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases",
          "Centers for Disease Control and Prevention"
        ],
        "confidence_by_section": {
          "Introduction": 0.9,
          "Background": 0.8,
          "Key Differences": 0.9,
          "Conclusion": 0.9
        },
        "overall_confidence": 0.85,
        "caveats": [
          "This assumes the reader is familiar with the basic concepts of bacteria and viruses."
        ],
        "alternative_interpretations": [
          "Considering antiviral medications as an alternative treatment option."
        ]
      },
      "raw_output": "<json_response>\n{\n  \"draft_response\": \"# Why Antibiotics are Ineffective Against Viral Infections\\n\\n## Introduction\\nAntibiotics are commonly used to treat bacterial infections, but they are ineffective against viral infections. This is because antibiotics target bacterial cells, not viral cells.\\n\\n## Background\\nViral infections occur when a virus enters the body and starts to replicate. Viruses are made up of genetic material (either DNA or RNA) surrounded by a protein coat. In contrast, bacterial cells have a cell wall and a defined nucleus. Antibiotics work by interfering with bacterial cell wall synthesis or protein synthesis, which ultimately kills the bacterial cell.\\n\\n## Key Differences\\n1. Cell structure: Bacterial cells have a cell wall and a defined nucleus, while viral cells do not.\\n2. Replication mechanism: Viruses replicate by hijacking the host cell's machinery, whereas bacteria replicate by dividing and growing.\\n3. Response to antibiotics: Bacteria respond to antibiotics by producing enzymes to inactivate them, while viruses do not.\\n\\n## Conclusion\\nIn summary, antibiotics are ineffective against viral infections because they target bacterial cells, not viral cells. This highlights the importance of selecting the correct treatment for a given infection.\\n\\n## Sources Needed\\n- [National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases](https://www.niaid.nih.gov/)\\n- [Centers for Disease Control and Prevention](https://www.cdc.gov/)\\n\\n## Confidence by Section\\n- Introduction: 0.9\\n- Background: 0.8\\n- Key Differences: 0.9\\n- Conclusion: 0.9\\n\\n## Overall Confidence\\n0.85\\n\\n## Caveats\\nThis response assumes that the reader is familiar with the basic concepts of bacteria and viruses.\\n\\n## Alternative Interpretations\\nAnother way to view this topic is to consider the concept of antiviral medications, which are designed to target viral infections directly.\\n\",\n  \"key_claims\": [\"Antibiotics target bacterial cells, not viral cells.\", \"Bacterial cells have a cell wall and a defined nucleus, while viral cells do not.\"],\n  \"sources_needed\": [\"National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases\", \"Centers for Disease Control and Prevention\"],\n  \"confidence_by_section\": {\"Introduction\": 0.9, \"Background\": 0.8, \"Key Differences\": 0.9, \"Conclusion\": 0.9},\n  \"overall_confidence\": 0.85,\n  \"caveats\": [\"This assumes the reader is familiar with the basic concepts of bacteria and viruses.\"],\n  \"alternative_interpretations\": [\"Considering antiviral medications as an alternative treatment option.\"]\n}\n</json_response>",
