      "id": "node_draft_2",
      "type": "draft",
      "goal": "Generate initial response",
      "inputs": [
        "node_clarify_2"
      ],
      "content": {
        "draft_response": "# Antibiotics and Viral Infections\n\nAntibiotics are not effective against viral infections, despite their widespread use. This is because viruses and bacteria operate differently at a cellular level, making it challenging for antibiotics to target and kill viruses.\n\n## Why Antibiotics Won't Work Against Viruses\n\n- Antibiotics target bacterial cell walls, which are composed of a rigid cell wall that surrounds the cell membrane. Viruses, on the other hand, lack a cell wall and rely on the host cell's machinery to replicate.\n\n- Antibiotics work by inhibiting the growth and division of bacterial cells. However, viruses hijack the host cell's machinery to replicate, making it difficult for antibiotics to target the viral replication process.\n\n## The Consequences of Misusing Antibiotics\n\n1. Overuse of antibiotics contributes to the development of antibiotic-resistant bacteria, making it challenging to treat bacterial infections in the future.\n\n2. The misuse of antibiotics can disrupt the balance of the microbiome, leading to a range of health issues, including digestive problems and allergies.\n\n## Alternative Approaches to Viral Infections\n\n> When treating viral infections, it's essential to opt for antiviral medications or supportive care rather than antibiotics.\n\n* Antiviral medications target specific viral enzymes and can help alleviate symptoms and slow disease progression.\n\n## Conclusion\n\n# Conclusion\n\nIn conclusion, antibiotics are not effective against viral infections. It's essential to understand the differences between bacterial and viral infections to avoid misusing antibiotics and to seek alternative treatments.\n\n",
        "key_claims": [
          "Antibiotics target bacterial cell walls",
          "Antibiotics work by inhibiting bacterial growth and division",
          "Viruses lack a cell wall and hijack host cell machinery",
          "Misusing antibiotics contributes to antibiotic-resistant bacteria",
          "Misusing antibiotics can disrupt the balance of the microbiome"
        ],
        "sources_needed": [
          "Textbook of Microbiology",
          "Journal of Antimicrobial Chemotherapy",
          "National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases"
        ],
        "confidence_by_section": {
          "intro": 0.9,
          "body": 0.8,
          "conclusion": 0.9
        },
        "overall_confidence": 0.85,
        "caveats": [
          "This assumes conventional medicine is being discussed.",
          "This response focuses on the general principles of antibiotics and viral infections."
        ],
        "alternative_interpretations": [
          "Another way to view this is to consider the role of antibiotics in treating bacterial infections."
        ]
      },
      "raw_output": "<json_response>\n{\n  \"draft_response\": \"# Antibiotics and Viral Infections\\n\\nAntibiotics are not effective against viral infections, despite their widespread use. This is because viruses and bacteria operate differently at a cellular level, making it challenging for antibiotics to target and kill viruses.\\n\\n## Why Antibiotics Won't Work Against Viruses\\n\\n- Antibiotics target bacterial cell walls, which are composed of a rigid cell wall that surrounds the cell membrane. Viruses, on the other hand, lack a cell wall and rely on the host cell's machinery to replicate.\\n\\n- Antibiotics work by inhibiting the growth and division of bacterial cells. However, viruses hijack the host cell's machinery to replicate, making it difficult for antibiotics to target the viral replication process.\\n\\n## The Consequences of Misusing Antibiotics\\n\\n1. Overuse of antibiotics contributes to the development of antibiotic-resistant bacteria, making it challenging to treat bacterial infections in the future.\\n\\n2. The misuse of antibiotics can disrupt the balance of the microbiome, leading to a range of health issues, including digestive problems and allergies.\\n\\n## Alternative Approaches to Viral Infections\\n\\n> When treating viral infections, it's essential to opt for antiviral medications or supportive care rather than antibiotics.\\n\\n* Antiviral medications target specific viral enzymes and can help alleviate symptoms and slow disease progression.\\n\\n## Conclusion\\n\\n# Conclusion\\n\\nIn conclusion, antibiotics are not effective against viral infections. It's essential to understand the differences between bacterial and viral infections to avoid misusing antibiotics and to seek alternative treatments.\\n\\n\",\n  \"key_claims\": [\"Antibiotics target bacterial cell walls\", \"Antibiotics work by inhibiting bacterial growth and division\", \"Viruses lack a cell wall and hijack host cell machinery\", \"Misusing antibiotics contributes to antibiotic-resistant bacteria\", \"Misusing antibiotics can disrupt the balance of the microbiome\"],\n  \"sources_needed\": [\"Textbook of Microbiology\", \"Journal of Antimicrobial Chemotherapy\", \"National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases\"],\n  \"confidence_by_section\": {\"intro\": 0.9, \"body\": 0.8, \"conclusion\": 0.9},\n  \"overall_confidence\": 0.85,\n  \"caveats\": [\"This assumes conventional medicine is being discussed.\", \"This response focuses on the general principles of antibiotics and viral infections.\"],\n  \"alternative_interpretations\": [\"Another way to view this is to consider the role of antibiotics in treating bacterial infections.\"]\n}\n</json_response>",
