      "raw_output": "<json_response>\n{\n  \"draft_response\": \"# Antibiotics and Viral Infections\\n\\n## Why Antibiotics are Not Effective Against Viral Infections\\n\\nAntibiotics are medications designed to target and kill bacterial infections. However, they are ineffective against viral infections because viruses are not living cells and therefore do not respond to antibiotics.\\n\\n- Viruses are not susceptible to antibiotics, which are specifically designed to target bacterial cell walls and protein synthesis.\n- Antibiotics can have side effects and contribute to antibiotic resistance when used unnecessarily.\n- The misuse of antibiotics in humans and animals has led to the development of antibiotic-resistant bacteria, making it harder to treat bacterial infections.\n\\n\\n## The Importance of Proper Antibiotic Use\\n\\n1. Antibiotics should only be prescribed by a healthcare professional for bacterial infections.\n2. It is essential to complete the full course of antibiotics as prescribed to prevent antibiotic resistance and ensure the infection is fully cleared.\n\\n\\n> Always consult a healthcare professional before taking antibiotics or any medication.\\n\\n[Read more about antibiotic use and resistance](https://www.cdc.gov/antibiotic-use/index.html)\",\n  \"key_claims\": [\"Antibiotics are ineffective against viral infections\", \"Antibiotics should be used judiciously to prevent antibiotic resistance\"],\n  \"sources_needed\": [\"Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC)\", \"World Health Organization (WHO)\"],\n  \"confidence_by_section\": {\"intro\": 0.9, \"body\": 0.8},\n  \"overall_confidence\": 0.85,\n  \"caveats\": [\"This assumes a general understanding of antibiotics and viral infections; consult a healthcare professional for specific advice.\"],\n  \"alternative_interpretations\": [\"Antibiotics may be effective against certain viral infections, such as bacterial superinfections that occur in conjunction with viral infections.\"]\n}\n